00:00:04.740 --> 00:00:16.080
I'm Norman Wobberger. Today we're carrying on&nbsp;
with this new approach to box arithmetic where we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:16.080 --> 00:00:23.400
are trying to put the duality between objects and&nbsp;
anti-objects sort of foremost in our arithmetic.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:24.540 --> 00:00:32.580
This is a very novel approach to arithmetic&nbsp;
because it's really building on a 20th-century&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:32.580 --> 00:00:40.500
physics understanding discovery of the fundamental&nbsp;
duality between particles and anti-particles in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.500 --> 00:00:46.320
our sort of subatomic world, which is really a&nbsp;
remarkable development in 20th-century physics&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.320 --> 00:00:52.800
and really ought to rank up there with relativity&nbsp;
and quantum mechanics in terms of the significance&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.800 --> 00:01:00.960
of it. So what we're going to do today is&nbsp;
to proceed by more or less concentrating on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:06.240
notation nomenclature. I'm going to introduce&nbsp;
variants to the things that I've already been&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:06.240 --> 00:01:12.660
talking about now with this view of trying&nbsp;
to put this duality center stage for us.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:13.260 --> 00:01:20.520
Okay, so roughly what we're going to do is if we&nbsp;
have some object, then the anti-object will be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.520 --> 00:01:27.480
denoted by a hyphen object. That's our general&nbsp;
orientation, okay? That will be used quite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:33.840
frequently and correspondingly&nbsp;
when we want to talk about both&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:33.840 --> 00:01:39.480
these objects, whatever they are, and the&nbsp;
anti-objects together, I propose to include them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.140 --> 00:01:48.000
in a bigger sort of category or classification&nbsp;
by using a capital letter. So in this case,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:55.200
capital O object. Okay, so a capital O object&nbsp;
will include both these little o objects and their&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.740 --> 00:02:01.140
anti-objects. So that's just a very general&nbsp;
kind of thing. So let's see how it works for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:01.860 --> 00:02:07.380
these boxes and the arithmetic of them. So&nbsp;
the basic idea is that we're going to build&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:07.380 --> 00:02:14.280
up arithmetic using boxes, and now centrally,&nbsp;
crucially, we are going to suppose that we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.280 --> 00:02:21.000
two different kinds of boxes: black boxes and red&nbsp;
boxes, okay? Not just one, we have two different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:27.480
kinds, and these are somehow opposite or antis&nbsp;
of each other. So we'll agree that the black ones&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.480 --> 00:02:35.760
are to be denoted by boxes. These are the boxes,&nbsp;
and the anti-objects or A boxes will be denoted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:41.520
in red. So if we have some box with something&nbsp;
inside it, let's say it's the box called B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:50.400
and then we consider a very identical box which&nbsp;
has the same things inside it but now has a red&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:50.400 --> 00:02:58.020
boundary instead of a black boundary, then we'll&nbsp;
refer to this as B super A or the anti of B.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.740 --> 00:03:07.980
Okay, now both these little B boxes and the&nbsp;
A little B boxes are included in the broader&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:14.160
classification of capital B boxes. Okay, so when&nbsp;
we write capital B, then we're referring to both&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.180 --> 00:03:24.480
objects in black as well as their anti-objects in&nbsp;
red. Okay, so to start the story, we look at the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:24.480 --> 00:03:30.240
simplest kind of boxes, which are the zero boxes,&nbsp;
but now there are two of them, not one. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:37.980
so our world starts with two things: the&nbsp;
empty black box, just an ordinary box,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:37.980 --> 00:03:45.120
and its anti-object, you know, in red. It's a&nbsp;
red box, so I'll refer to this first one as zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:45.120 --> 00:03:51.300
and we'll refer to the second one, the red one,&nbsp;
as anti-zero or A0, consistent with our notation.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:56.580
And when we write it numerically, we'll write&nbsp;
just an ordinary zero for this black one and a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:56.580 --> 00:04:03.900
zero with an A superscript for the anti-zero&nbsp;
or A zero. And both of these together will&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:10.980
be included in this type called capital zero.&nbsp;
Okay, so when we talk about a capital zero, we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:10.980 --> 00:04:16.320
could be either talking about this zero here, this&nbsp;
black one, or this anti-zero here, this red one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:24.960
Okay, what can we do with just zeros? Well, we&nbsp;
can add them. Now, when we were just talking about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.160 --> 00:04:31.680
M-sets before, we just had empty M-sets, and then&nbsp;
it was obvious that the empty M-set plus the empty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:31.680 --> 00:04:37.860
M-set was the empty M-set, but now things are a&nbsp;
little more complicated because we have these two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:37.860 --> 00:04:46.800
kinds of fundamental zero objects, so we have to&nbsp;
specify the addition for all possible pairs. So a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:46.800 --> 00:04:56.100
black empty box plus a black empty box is another&nbsp;
black empty box, and similarly, a red anti-zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:56.880 --> 00:05:08.880
plus a red anti-zero is a black box or a zero. And&nbsp;
otherwise, black plus red equals red, and red plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:14.460
black equals red. So we could say this also in&nbsp;
the language of zeros and anti-zeros. So zero plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.460 --> 00:05:21.180
zero is zero, zero plus anti-zero is anti-zero,&nbsp;
anti-zero plus zero is anti-zero, and anti-zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:21.180 --> 00:05:28.740
plus anti-zero is zero. So this is a pretty&nbsp;
fundamental kind of thing, and we justify this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.700 --> 00:05:36.660
because we want the arithmetic that we are&nbsp;
going to create to be somewhat consistent. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:37.740 --> 00:05:45.180
and so this is a good way to proceed. Okay, now&nbsp;
we can extend this consistently to sums of more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:45.180 --> 00:05:51.360
boxes or anti-boxes, in this case, just zero&nbsp;
boxes. So for example, if we have an anti-zero&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:51.360 --> 00:05:56.280
and a zero and a zero and a zero and an anti-zero&nbsp;
and an anti-zero, and we add them all up, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:56.280 --> 00:06:01.740
so then we can do it in a number of ways, but we&nbsp;
can just think about really what what's crucial&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:01.740 --> 00:06:09.660
is the number of anti-zeros. So that's going&nbsp;
to determine the type of the resulting thing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:09.660 --> 00:06:16.080
In this case, there's an odd number of red ones&nbsp;
or an odd number of anti-zeros, so the result is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.080 --> 00:06:23.460
going to be another anti-zero. Zero anti, so the&nbsp;
sum depends only on the parity of the number of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:28.740
anti-boxes. If there are an even number of&nbsp;
anti-boxes, then the result is zero, while&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:28.740 --> 00:06:37.020
if there are an odd number of anti-boxes, then the&nbsp;
result is anti-zero. Okay, so now we're going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:44.280
define recursively what a box&nbsp;
is, what a capital B box is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:45.600 --> 00:06:52.560
and we're going to start the initial objects&nbsp;
are the two zero boxes: the zero box and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:52.560 --> 00:07:00.540
anti-zero box. Okay, and we declare that these are&nbsp;
both capital B boxes. Okay, and then there's only&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:00.540 --> 00:07:08.100
one more thing, which is a kind of an inductive&nbsp;
definition. So we agree that if we have X, Y,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:08.100 --> 00:07:16.080
up to say Z, these are already defined boxes,&nbsp;
capital B boxes, then we'll agree that so are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:17.100 --> 00:07:28.620
these two things: the black box containing X and Y&nbsp;
and so on up to Z, call it A, and the anti of that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:28.620 --> 00:07:35.460
object, which is a red box containing exactly&nbsp;
the same elements containing X, Y, up to Z.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:36.240 --> 00:07:40.380
Okay, so this thing here is a box because it's&nbsp;
black. This thing is an anti-box because it's red,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.380 --> 00:07:45.300
and these are antis of each other because&nbsp;
the contents are otherwise exactly the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.300 --> 00:07:51.180
same. The only difference between these&nbsp;
two is the color of the bounding box.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:52.980 --> 00:07:58.620
Okay, and just a little bit of additional&nbsp;
notation: we'll say that in this case, X, Y,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.620 --> 00:08:11.100
up to Z, these are the elements of the capital B&nbsp;
boxes A or anti-A. So this is really the story of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:11.100 --> 00:08:15.720
the objects that we're going to be considering.&nbsp;
We're just going to create recursively&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:17.040 --> 00:08:26.280
more and more complicated boxes, capital B boxes,&nbsp;
by recursively creating boxes by nesting them. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.280 --> 00:08:31.140
once we have nested boxes, then we can use&nbsp;
those as elements of further nested boxes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.140 --> 00:08:37.920
and that's what our arithmetic is going&nbsp;
to consist of. And that's going to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:37.920 --> 00:08:43.140
a much wider and bigger arithmetic than we&nbsp;
currently have. Okay, much wider and bigger.

00:08:46.980 --> 00:08:47.520
foreign

00:08:48.420 --> 00:09:00.180
To distinguish these two types of capital B&nbsp;
boxes, we'll say that a box is a capital box&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.180 --> 00:09:06.720
of positive type, and we'll denote the positive&nbsp;
type by this particular symbol like a plus sign&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:06.720 --> 00:09:13.620
with a circle around it. Okay, not to be confused&nbsp;
with addition. So this is just a symbol denoting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:13.620 --> 00:09:21.960
this positive type, which is associated with a&nbsp;
box that is something that's got black around it.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:22.920 --> 00:09:29.400
Similarly, an anti-box or A box is a capital&nbsp;
box of negative type. It will be denoted by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:29.400 --> 00:09:35.700
a minus sign. This is not a theta; it's&nbsp;
a minus sign enclosed in a circle. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:35.700 --> 00:09:42.000
so these are the two possible types of a capital&nbsp;
box. You know, a capital box you can ask is it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:42.000 --> 00:09:47.160
either a positive type or a negative type, and&nbsp;
to tell you just look at the color of the outside&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:53.040
box. If it's black, then it's positive; if it's&nbsp;
red, it's negative, independent of what's inside.

00:09:55.260 --> 00:10:05.700
Okay, so then we can express this summation of&nbsp;
zeros, this aspect of counting the number of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:12.660
anti-boxes, by saying that the sum of zeros is&nbsp;
a zero, again, whose type is the product of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.660 --> 00:10:18.240
types of the constituents. Okay, well, so we have&nbsp;
to define what we mean by a product of types. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:18.240 --> 00:10:24.300
that's sort of the obvious thing. So we'll agree&nbsp;
that positive times positive is positive, negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:24.300 --> 00:10:29.220
times negative is positive, positive times&nbsp;
negative is negative, and negative times positive&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:29.220 --> 00:10:35.880
is positive. So that's just the same as it is&nbsp;
in ordinary life. Okay, so that's how we can say&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:37.260 --> 00:10:45.240
how to determine the type of a sum of zeros,&nbsp;
let's say, but in fact, of more general boxes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:54.000
So for example, here, here we've got three&nbsp;
black boxes and three red boxes. These are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:54.000 --> 00:10:58.680
the corresponding types underneath the plus or&nbsp;
positive type, positive type, negative type,&nbsp;&nbsp;

