00:19:52.200 --> 00:19:59.760
in mind the colors of the boxes, either black or&nbsp;
red. So to add capital boxes, what are we going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:59.760 --> 00:20:05.160
do? We're going to form a new capital box whose&nbsp;
elements are all the elements of the original&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:06.300 --> 00:20:12.300
capital boxes and whose type is the product&nbsp;
of the types of the original capital boxes.

00:20:14.520 --> 00:20:18.960
So we're going to do just as we did before, we&nbsp;
take the contents of all these capital boxes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:18.960 --> 00:20:23.340
that means they could be boxes or anti-boxes,&nbsp;
the outsides could be black or red,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:23.340 --> 00:20:28.260
we're going to dump them all out. Okay,&nbsp;
the elements all get put into another box,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:28.260 --> 00:20:34.680
but the color of that new box now has to be&nbsp;
determined. It's determined by the color of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:34.680 --> 00:20:41.760
all the various original boxes that we are taking&nbsp;
the stuff dumping out of. Okay, so we have to take&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:49.620
the product of the types of the original boxes to&nbsp;
determine the type or the color of the final box.

00:20:52.680 --> 00:20:59.280
So for example, here we're adding&nbsp;
these three boxes. All right, so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:00.360 --> 00:21:04.260
first what we do is we just take the&nbsp;
elements and dump them out into a box.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:04.260 --> 00:21:09.180
So these two guys here get copied there,&nbsp;
these two guys here are copied down here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:09.180 --> 00:21:14.160
and these guys here are copied here. Okay,&nbsp;
and then we put this in a box, but we have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:14.160 --> 00:21:18.660
determine what's the color of this bounding&nbsp;
box. So we go up to here and we say, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:18.660 --> 00:21:23.820
these are type, well, this is a negative type,&nbsp;
this is a positive type, this is a positive type.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:24.480 --> 00:21:30.120
So the product of those types is negative,&nbsp;
that's why we have a red bounding box.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:31.620 --> 00:21:38.460
But there is some simplification possible here&nbsp;
because this thing here and this one here are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:38.460 --> 00:21:44.820
antis of each other, so they're going to cancel.&nbsp;
Okay, and also this zero and this anti-zero are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:44.820 --> 00:21:51.660
also going to cancel, so we're just going to be&nbsp;
left with this object here and this one here.

00:21:54.900 --> 00:22:02.880
So we get an anti-box overall since negative&nbsp;
times positive times positive is negative.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:04.620 --> 00:22:08.460
And we note that the sum of natural&nbsp;
numbers is also a natural number,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:09.180 --> 00:22:15.960
and the sum of capital integers is also&nbsp;
a capital integer. We get, however, an a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:15.960 --> 00:22:23.760
integer if there's an odd number of a integers in&nbsp;
the sum, and otherwise we get an integer. Okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:23.760 --> 00:22:30.240
and now we have a result that we can convince&nbsp;
ourselves of, that in this great generality&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:30.240 --> 00:22:37.140
of addition of arbitrary capital boxes, that&nbsp;
it's actually commutative and it's associative.

00:22:41.100 --> 00:22:48.780
Now I can talk about the multiplication of capital&nbsp;
boxes. So to form the product a times b of capital&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:48.780 --> 00:22:56.640
boxes A and B, we take the capital box of all&nbsp;
possible sums a plus b or little a plus little b,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:56.640 --> 00:23:03.240
where little a belongs to A, in other words, is&nbsp;
an element of A, and little b is an element of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:03.240 --> 00:23:10.920
B. And of course, we have to take each element&nbsp;
with the corresponding multiplicity, that is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:10.920 --> 00:23:16.380
we're going to take each element no matter how&nbsp;
many times the similar kind of thing appears,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:17.160 --> 00:23:24.840
where the type of a times B, so the resulting&nbsp;
type of this big box is the product of the types&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:24.840 --> 00:23:34.200
of A and B. So it's the same rule as we used for&nbsp;
the addition of boxes, also for multiplication.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:36.180 --> 00:23:42.900
So in terms of a special case, the special case&nbsp;
is just the products of zeros, of capital zeros,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:43.500 --> 00:23:50.280
and that multiplication table is just like the&nbsp;
addition multiplication table. So 0 times 0 is 0,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:50.280 --> 00:23:54.480
0 times anti-zero is anti-zero,&nbsp;
anti-zero times zero is anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:54.480 --> 00:24:00.840
and anti-zero times anti-zero is zero. And&nbsp;
I remind you that we had justification,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:00.840 --> 00:24:10.320
we had good reason for defining things this way,&nbsp;
but curiously, it is a table which is identical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:10.320 --> 00:24:16.140
to the addition table for capital zeros. And&nbsp;
of course, we notice, as we have before, that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:16.140 --> 00:24:22.620
there are some curiosities about this, maybe even&nbsp;
some disconcerting aspects, in particular this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:23.220 --> 00:24:31.860
property that 0 times anti-0 is anti-zero. That's&nbsp;
disconcerting because it's different from the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:31.860 --> 00:24:38.460
familiar rule that zero times anything is zero,&nbsp;
right? That's a rule that we're used to for any a,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:38.460 --> 00:24:45.600
but this does not hold here. It holds much of&nbsp;
the time, but it does not hold when capital A&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:45.600 --> 00:24:51.420
is an anti-zero. In that case, the right-hand&nbsp;
side is not zero, it is rather anti-zero.

00:24:53.760 --> 00:25:02.580
Okay, and here's an example. So here's a box&nbsp;
A, and here's an anti-box B. Okay, the roof&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:02.580 --> 00:25:09.180
is missing there. There it is. Okay, and so to&nbsp;
take their product, what do we do? Well, we have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:09.180 --> 00:25:15.360
to take all possible sums. So we start with this&nbsp;
one here, maybe this box here plus this one here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:15.360 --> 00:25:21.480
and then this one plus this one, and this one&nbsp;
plus this one. So this first row we're adding&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:21.480 --> 00:25:27.000
this empty box to each one of these three. And so&nbsp;
now for the second row, the second element here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:27.600 --> 00:25:32.460
first of all, I'll add it to this thing and then&nbsp;
add it to this one and then add it to this one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:32.460 --> 00:25:40.020
We get these guys here, and so now we have to&nbsp;
evaluate these by our prior notion over addition.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:40.020 --> 00:25:46.380
So we do that. So adding zero to something&nbsp;
doesn't change it, so we get just this thing here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:46.380 --> 00:25:51.960
this thing here, this thing here. And then when we&nbsp;
do the sum here, okay, here we have summation, so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:51.960 --> 00:25:58.260
we're going to get three black boxes inside, but&nbsp;
the outside is going to be black because negative&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:58.260 --> 00:26:05.100
times negative is positive. Over here, we have&nbsp;
negative times positive, so we're going to get an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:05.100 --> 00:26:13.140
anti-box with two black boxes inside. And,&nbsp;
is that right, with two black boxes inside?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:14.280 --> 00:26:17.880
No, not with three things inside. That should&nbsp;
actually be two things inside, shouldn't it?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:19.020 --> 00:26:25.440
Because we're just adding this thing here to&nbsp;
that, yes. So pardon me, this thing here should&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:25.440 --> 00:26:31.740
be eliminated. It's just a red box with two black&nbsp;
boxes inside it. And lastly, this thing here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:31.740 --> 00:26:37.740
have I done that one right? We've got four black&nbsp;
boxes, yes, and the type of the bounding box is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:39.240 --> 00:26:44.880
negative, so it's really red. Okay, so it's&nbsp;
almost correct. A calculation of A times B,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:45.720 --> 00:26:53.040
and then we have a theorem that multiplication&nbsp;
of boxes is also commutative and associative.

00:26:55.500 --> 00:26:58.500
Now that we have both addition and&nbsp;
multiplication of general boxes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:58.500 --> 00:27:04.620
we can ask about how they relate. To&nbsp;
what extent does the distributive law,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:04.620 --> 00:27:12.900
which is this thing here, hold that A plus B&nbsp;
times C should be A times C plus B times C?

00:27:15.600 --> 00:27:22.320
Okay, so we've already observed that the&nbsp;
distributive law doesn't always hold, and that's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:22.320 --> 00:27:29.460
evident even just at the level of the zeros, the&nbsp;
capital zeros. Because if we have a zero plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:29.460 --> 00:27:35.640
an anti-zero and we multiply it by anti-zero,&nbsp;
and zero plus anti-zero is anti-zero, so we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:35.640 --> 00:27:40.500
getting into zero times anti-zero, which is zero.&nbsp;
On the other hand, the distributive law asks us&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:40.500 --> 00:27:47.700
to calculate zero times anti-zero plus anti-zero&nbsp;
times anti-zero. This thing here is anti-zero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:47.700 --> 00:27:55.080
this thing here is zero, and their sum is&nbsp;
anti-zero. So the distributive law does not hold&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:55.080 --> 00:28:02.520
generally. That's a little bit disconcerting, but&nbsp;
it's actually not that bad when we realize that we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:02.520 --> 00:28:09.060
have the following result: that the distributive&nbsp;
law actually holds for A, B, and C boxes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:09.780 --> 00:28:16.920
that is, their black things. Okay, so I'm going&nbsp;
to just show you why that is so in considerable&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:16.920 --> 00:28:24.720
generality. Suppose that there are three boxes, A,&nbsp;
B, and C, and A has, say, elements X, Y, up to Z.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:24.720 --> 00:28:34.680
B has elements K, L, up to M, and C has elements&nbsp;
P, Q, up to R. Okay, then when we calculate A plus&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:34.680 --> 00:28:42.720
B times C, so there's A plus B, just the sum of&nbsp;
the two M sets, and it's going to be black, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:42.720 --> 00:28:50.580
times C. Here C, which roof is up here. So what&nbsp;
we're going to get is we're going to get the M set&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:50.580 --> 00:28:55.860
of all possible sums, and since it's black times&nbsp;
black, we're going to get black. Okay, so it's&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:55.860 --> 00:29:02.160
positive times positive is going to be positive.&nbsp;
So we're going to get elements X plus P, X plus Q,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:02.160 --> 00:29:12.120
up to X plus R, and then Y plus P, Y plus Q, up to&nbsp;
Y plus R, and then Z plus P, all the way up to Z&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:12.120 --> 00:29:19.440
plus P, Z plus Q, Z plus R from that top row, and&nbsp;
then down here K plus P, K plus Q, up to K plus R,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:19.440 --> 00:29:26.880
L plus P, L plus Q, up to L plus R, all the&nbsp;
way up to M plus P, M plus Q, up to M plus R.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:27.540 --> 00:29:33.420
On the other hand, when we look at the other side&nbsp;
of the distributive law, A times C plus B times C.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:34.020 --> 00:29:42.660
So here they are again. Okay, so we have&nbsp;
to look at A times C plus B times C,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:43.620 --> 00:29:50.880
then what do we get? Well, here's A times C, so&nbsp;
X plus P, X plus Q, all the way up to X plus R,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:50.880 --> 00:29:57.060
then Y plus P, Y plus Q, up to Y plus R, all the&nbsp;
way up to Z plus P, Z plus Q, up to Z plus R,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:57.060 --> 00:30:02.820
and something similar for B times C. And then when&nbsp;
you look at these things and compare their sum&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:02.820 --> 00:30:11.160
with this, you see that you're getting exactly the&nbsp;
same elements. Okay, so yes, indeed, we do get A&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:11.160 --> 00:30:18.960
plus B times C, so things work because everything&nbsp;
is in black, and so the black times black is just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:18.960 --> 00:30:23.940
black. Okay, so we see that the problem with the&nbsp;
distributive law is not really a deep problem,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:23.940 --> 00:30:28.860
it's just sort of a surface problem having&nbsp;
to do with the color of that outside box.

00:30:30.900 --> 00:30:38.400
Okay, so now let's go to polynumbers, which&nbsp;
is actually sort of where most algebra takes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:38.400 --> 00:30:43.920
place. Okay, but now we have this sort of enlarged&nbsp;
point of view. So first of all, a definition: a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:43.920 --> 00:30:53.640
polynumber or a poly is a box of capital integers.&nbsp;
A box, so it's black. Okay, that's a small poly.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:54.300 --> 00:31:01.800
That's a type. An anti-polynumber or a&nbsp;
poly is an A box of capital integers.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:02.520 --> 00:31:10.380
That's type A poly there. Okay, so then a capital&nbsp;
polynumber or a capital poly is either a poly or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:10.380 --> 00:31:16.620
an anti-poly, and we have the type capital poly.&nbsp;
So this is a little bit different because formerly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:16.620 --> 00:31:22.620
we called these things integral polynumbers.&nbsp;
So roughly speaking, I want to elevate integer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:22.620 --> 00:31:30.360
arithmetic, that's sort of the nicest arithmetic&nbsp;
in some sense. Okay, and so our polys are going to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:30.360 --> 00:31:37.320
be associated with integer arithmetic, that's&nbsp;
sort of really nice algebra. So for example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:37.320 --> 00:31:44.760
the fundamental new poly that we get, okay, this&nbsp;
alpha thing is where we have a box inside a box&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:44.760 --> 00:31:51.120
inside a box, and what's inside here is the&nbsp;
number one. So this is a box containing one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:51.900 --> 00:31:56.760
Alpha squared will then be the square of this&nbsp;
thing, so we have to multiply this thing with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:56.760 --> 00:32:02.220
itself. That means we have to make a box whose&nbsp;
element is the sum of this thing and this thing.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:02.220 --> 00:32:06.900
So when we add these two things here, we're&nbsp;
getting one plus one, which is two. So we're&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:06.900 --> 00:32:12.900
getting the box which has a single two in&nbsp;
it, and so on. Alpha cubed will be the box&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:12.900 --> 00:32:17.760
containing a single three, etc. So for example,&nbsp;
we can combine these things. So this thing here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:17.760 --> 00:32:25.020
it's a box, it's got a zero there, a zero there, a&nbsp;
three there. So this thing is 2 plus alpha cubed.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:26.100 --> 00:32:31.320
But in the world of poly, there are now more&nbsp;
possibilities because these examples are all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:31.320 --> 00:32:36.900
just black things, but we can have black things&nbsp;
and red things. So in particular, this thing here&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:36.900 --> 00:32:41.700
is of interest. So we have a black box which&nbsp;
contains a red box which contains a black box.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:42.840 --> 00:32:50.220
So this is minus alpha or our preferred notation&nbsp;
alpha bar. Why is that? Well, because if you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:50.220 --> 00:32:55.140
take alpha, which is this, and you add it to this&nbsp;
thing, when you add these, you're going to get a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:55.140 --> 00:32:59.160
black box with this thing inside it and this thing&nbsp;
inside it, but these are antis of each other,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:59.160 --> 00:33:07.260
so they cancel, and you're just going to get zero.&nbsp;
All right, another possibility is this thing here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:07.260 --> 00:33:13.140
which is a black box containing a black box&nbsp;
containing a red box. That's alpha to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:13.140 --> 00:33:21.600
minus one or another way of looking at it, it's&nbsp;
the box containing minus one or one bar. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:21.600 --> 00:33:28.860
why is that? Well, because if we multiply alpha,&nbsp;
here's alpha with this object. Okay, then what we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:28.860 --> 00:33:34.200
have to do is we have to form the box because&nbsp;
we're taking the product of two boxes of this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:35.160 --> 00:33:41.460
box here and this box. Yes, now when we add these&nbsp;
two things, okay, when we add these two things,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:41.460 --> 00:33:47.040
well, the contents will annihilate each other,&nbsp;
and we're just going to get an empty box,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:47.040 --> 00:33:52.320
which is one. So that's why this thing deserves to&nbsp;
be called alpha to the minus one, because when we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:52.320 --> 00:33:59.460
multiply it by alpha, we get one or alpha to zero.&nbsp;
And you can check that another possibility is to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:59.460 --> 00:34:05.520
take a black box containing a red box containing&nbsp;
a red box. That's minus alpha to the minus one.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:06.840 --> 00:34:12.780
So that's just sort of the start of polynomial&nbsp;
arithmetic, but it's, as we've seen before,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:13.440 --> 00:34:20.700
in some sense, a bigger arithmetic than usual&nbsp;
because of the existence of these negative powers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:20.700 --> 00:34:27.600
of alpha playing essentially just as important&nbsp;
a role as positive powers. So this is a bit of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:27.600 --> 00:34:33.360
a departure from the calculus point of view&nbsp;
towards polynomials. It's a bigger picture.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:34.800 --> 00:34:40.380
And very briefly, then, of course, the next&nbsp;
stage up, there's a whole hierarchy of stages,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:40.380 --> 00:34:45.960
or maybe we should say the next stage down, are&nbsp;
those multi-numbers. Okay, and similarly, we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:45.960 --> 00:34:52.620
define a multi-number or a multi, that should&nbsp;
be a multi, is a box of capital polys. Well,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:52.620 --> 00:34:59.040
an a multi-number or an a multi is an a box of&nbsp;
capital polys, and then a capital multi-number&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:59.040 --> 00:35:03.360
or a capital multi is either a multi or&nbsp;
an anti-multi. And we have this new type,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:04.380 --> 00:35:10.380
and this world here is something of a new&nbsp;
world. We haven't explored it very much, okay,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:10.380 --> 00:35:15.840
but there will be some interesting twists&nbsp;
in this multi-number world, as we'll see,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:16.500 --> 00:35:25.020
but we can see this entire chasm of arithmetic&nbsp;
below us. So we're just at the top rungs with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:31.920
the usual algebra, polynomial algebra, and there's&nbsp;
this vast chasm underneath us with all kinds of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:31.920 --> 00:35:39.600
complexity because these things can be layered&nbsp;
and we could get blacks and reds layering in all&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:39.600 --> 00:35:45.600
kinds of interesting ways. And we should expect&nbsp;
that the behavior of these objects depends sort&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:45.600 --> 00:35:53.340
of on the relative colorings of these various&nbsp;
nested layers. So in principle, this is a huge&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:53.340 --> 00:35:59.280
and maybe sort of almost mind-blowing arithmetic&nbsp;
that we have in front of us, but lots to explore.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:59.280 --> 00:36:05.940
And of course, a crucial question is, you&nbsp;
know, is this the arithmetic of the world?

00:36:08.280 --> 00:36:10.560
I'm Norman Wobberger. Thanks for listening.

00:36:10.560 --> 00:36:13.719
